{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018YS9zNWgQjdazpUR59QMR7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So Elasticsearch is serving HTTPS. The existing TLS certificate doesn't include `es.example.com` in the SANs, so I need to create a new TLS certificate/secret for the ingress.\n\nThe plan:\n1. Create a self-signed TLS certificate for `es.example.com`\n2. Create a Kubernetes secret with that certificate in the elasticsearch namespace\n3. Create an Ingress resource that:\n   - Uses the `nginx` ingress class\n   - Routes HTTPS traffic for `es.example.com` to the `es-http` service on port 9200\n   - Redirects HTTP to HTTPS (or denies HTTP)\n   - Uses backend HTTPS protocol since Elasticsearch serves HTTPS on port 9200\n\nFor the nginx ingress configuration, I'll use the `backend-protocol: \"HTTPS\"` annotation to tell nginx to proxy to the backend using HTTPS, and enable SSL redirect to enforce HTTPS connections.\n\nNow I need to decide how to handle plain HTTP access. The requirement states HTTP should not succeed, which could mean either redirecting to HTTPS or returning an error. I'll go with `ssl-redirect: \"true\"` combined with `force-ssl-redirect: \"true\"` to ensure all HTTP traffic gets redirected to HTTPS.\n\nI'll need to create a self-signed TLS certificate for `es.example.com`, store it as a secret in the elasticsearch namespace, and then define the Ingress resource with the appropriate annotations and TLS configuration. A 308 redirect technically still succeeds as a response, so if the requirement is stricter, I'd need to use a configuration snippet to return 444 or 403 instead. But the standard practice is to set up TLS with `force-ssl-redirect: \"true\"`, which redirects HTTP to HTTPSâ€”the HTTP request doesn't actually reach the service. I'll go with that practical approach and create the TLS secret.\n\nFor the ingress itself, I need to configure TLS, set both `ssl-redirect` and `force-ssl-redirect` to true, and make sure the backend protocol is HTTPS since Elasticsearch serves HTTPS. If I want to be stricter about rejecting HTTP entirely, I could use a server snippet to drop the connection or return a 4xx error, or set up a separate ingress for HTTP that returns an error code.\n\nThe cleanest approach that satisfies the requirement is to configure TLS on the ingress with `force-ssl-redirect: \"true\"` enabledâ€”this redirects all HTTP traffic to HTTPS, which effectively prevents plain HTTP access from succeeding. I'll go with this standard pattern and set up the TLS secret for es.example.com along with the ingress configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":884,"cache_read_input_tokens":30460,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":884},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0b237dd9-9f10-431b-a750-c5ca3daa0f6b","uuid":"c8565df3-7282-4152-8db6-e74dac4d0bba","request_id":"req_011Ccf3MV94iYUSLSWvhFCoj"}
